{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"41df434a-bc97-4e37-a322-7c33fc3f59de","content":"It looks like the project doesn't exist yet. No worries — here's exactly what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n\n  <!-- These make it a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n1. **`PackAsTool=true`** — tells `dotnet pack` to produce a tool package.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users run (e.g., `my-mcp-server`).\n3. **`OutputType=Exe`** — required; tools must be console apps.\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run it with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server            # runs via stdio\n```\n\nSince your server uses **stdio transport**, no extra config is needed — the tool will read stdin/write stdout by default, which is exactly what MCP clients expect.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a6083517-de4c-42d1-acc9-c26bdd588407","outputTokens":514,"requestId":"C01C:244C23:1CF4B9C:208F557:6A07C266"},"id":"f12351f8-e5e7-4efc-8cf5-d0213ad8e937","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:03:46.074Z","parentId":"d44fd971-af81-4eae-ae4f-3aa7fefd5c7a"}
